  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In the NFL, during overtime, the rules regarding onside kicks are the same as in regulation play. The kicking team is allowed to attempt an onside kick. If the kicking team successfully recovers the ball, they retain possession and continue their drive. The other team does not automatically receive the ball afterward; it depends on the outcome of the next series of plays.\n\nAccording to the NFL overtime rules:\n1. Both teams must have the opportunity to possess the ball at least once unless the team receiving the kickoff scores a touchdown on its initial possession.\n2. If the team that receives the kickoff scores a field goal on its initial possession, the other team gets a chance to possess the ball.\n3. If the kicking team successfully recovers an onside kick and scores a touchdown on the resulting drive, the game ends.\n4. If the kicking team recovers an onside kick and scores only a field goal, then the other team still gets a chance to possess the ball.\n\nIn summary, upon a successful onside kick recovery in overtime, the kicking team continues their possession and play proceeds based on the rules of scoring from the possession.",
